#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
shadow_hand_simulation.py
─────────────────────────
Headless, step-locked MuJoCo digital twin for the Shadow Hand.

Operating principle
───────────────────
  This node does NOT run in real time.  Instead it advances the simulation
  by exactly CTRL_DT seconds of physics time per received command, then
  immediately publishes the resulting joint state.  The wall-clock pace is
  therefore set entirely by how fast Julia can produce commands — the
  simulation is as fast as possible.

  Before the first command arrives the node publishes the initial joint state
  at IDLE_HZ (10 Hz) so Julia can bootstrap its state estimate.

Experiment timeline  (t = 0 at first received command)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  t =  0 s   first command → logging starts, time origin set
  t = LIFT_TIME s  arm lift triggered automatically
  t = SIM_STOP_TIME s  simulation stops, plots and video shown

ROS interface
─────────────
  PUBLISH   /shadowhand_state_topic   sensor_msgs/JointState   24 hand joints
  SUBSCRIBE /shadowhand_command_topic std_msgs/Float64MultiArray  24 joint targets

Joint ordering
──────────────
  Published joints   : JOINT_NAMES  (24 entries, read from qpos)
  Subscribed commands: 24 values in JOINT_NAMES order (written to data.ctrl)

Coupling mode (auto-detected at startup from the loaded MJCF)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  COUPLED   rh_A_FFJ0/MFJ0/RFJ0/LFJ0 each drive J2+J1 via tendon.
            J1+J2 command targets are summed before writing to the J0 actuator.
  UNCOUPLED Every joint has its own actuator; commands map 1-to-1.

Video recording
───────────────
  Frames are captured via MuJoCo's offscreen renderer at VIDEO_FPS.
  At the end a preview is displayed; the user is prompted to save or discard.
"""

